subSection.paragraph:
The 

Botrytis

genus comprises a wide range of fungal species found world-wide (
Agrios et al., 2005
; 
Coley-Smith et al., 1980
). The species 

Botrytis cinerea
Persoon

: Fries (
Sclerotiniaceae
) was first characterized by Micheli in 1729 and later confirmed by Persoon in 1801. Many other species have been described since then thanks to advances in molecular genetic techniques and today there are approximately 30 different 

Botrytis
species.

Seven new species, a hybrid, and a species complex have been isolated and identified over the last ten years (
Elad et al., 2016a
). 

B. cinerea
(teleomorph: 
Botryotinia fuckeliana
)

is the causal agent of grey mold disease that affects a total of 586 genera of vascular plants, representing over 1400 ornamental and agriculturally important plant species (
Elad et al., 2016b
; 
Fillinger and Elad 2016
). This fungus is a typical necrotroph whose infective cycle includes the killing of plant cells, maceration of plant tissue and then reproduction by forming asexual spores on the decomposing plant material. Throughout the infection, 

B. cinerea

uses a battery of phytotoxins, enzymes, and reactive oxygen species (
Rossi et al., 2011
). Two groups of phytotoxins have been identified (
Fig. 1
), i.e. the sesquiterpene botrydial (
1
) and related compounds (
Colmenares et al., 2002
) and the polyketides: botcinic and botcineric acid (
2
, 
3
) and their botcinin derivatives (
4
, 
5
) (
Tani et al., 2005
, 
2006
), as well as botrylactone, (
6
) (
Moraga et al., 2011
) an intermediate in the biosynthetic route to 
4
and 
5
. Furthermore, a structurally different group of compounds with the same polyketide chain as that of botcinins (
4, 5
), whose main representative is cinbotolide A (
7
) (
Botubol et al., 2014
) and the sesquiterpenoid abscisic acid (
8
), have been isolated from several strains of 

Botrytis
(
Marumo et al., 1982
)

. * Corresponding author.

The biosynthetic route and the polyketide synthases involved in the biosynthesis of botcinin and its derivatives and botrylactones (compounds 
2–6
) have been described in the literature (
Massaroli et al., 2013
; 
Porquier et al., 2019
). Biosynthesis was studied by using acetate and malonate units labelled with deuterium and carbon thirteen. It has been shown that the condensation of an acetate starter unit and four molecules of malonate yields a pentaketide (C10), with its four pendent methyl group originating from L-methylmethionine. The pentaketide losses the starter unit of the acetate to give botcinic and botcineric acid derivatives and their relatives botcinins (
Massaroli et al., 2013
).

