Metabolites were purified by column chromatography (CC) and semipreparative and analytical HPLC (Su´arez et al., 2018; 
Moraga et al., 2011
). HPLC was performed with a Hitachi/Merck L-6270 apparatus equipped with an UV-VIS detector (L 4250) and a differential refractometer detector (RI-7490). Lichrosfer Si 60 (5 μm) LichoCart (
250 mm
× 
4 mm
) and Lichrosfer Si 60 (10 μm) LichoCart (
250 mm
× 
10 mm
) columns were used for isolation experiments. Optical rotation was recorded with a digital polarimeter. IR spectra were determined on an FT-IR spectrophotometer and reported as wave number (cm 
1
) (
Botubol et al., 2014
).

10 days after inoculation, the solid agar malt medium was extracted (
Moraga et al., 2016
; 
Dalmais et al., 2011
) yielding a dense oil from the 

bcbot4
Δ

culture (
300 mg
) that was separated by column chromatography on silica gel, eluted with mixtures containing increasing percentages of ethyl acetate/hexane (10–100%) and methanol as solvents. The final purification of the metabolites of interest was carried out by means of semipreparative HPLC using 
n
-hexane (Hex)-ethyl acetate (EtOAc) – acetone (Me 
2
CO) (50:40:10) or Hex-EtOAc-Me 
2
CO (70:20:10) as the mobile phase and flow rate 0.8 or 2.5 ml min 
1
(
Moraga et al., 2011
), yielding the metabolite presilphiperfolan-8β- ol (
Pinedo et al., 2008
) and a significant number of metabolites with a polyketide skeleton. In addition to the known polyketides: botcinic and botcineric acids (
2
, 
3
) (5.0, 
3.5 mg
), botcinins A (
4
), B (
5
), E and G (50.5, 30.4, 8.0, 6.0 mg), (
Tani et al., 2005
, 
2006
), botrylactone (
6
) (
20 mg
) (
Moraga et al., 2011
), cinbotolide (
7
) (
10 mg
) (
Botubol et al., 2014
); the botrylactones 5-hydroxy-7-(4-hydroxydec-2 (3)-enoyl)botrylactone (
12.2 mg
), 5-hydroxy-7-(oct-2 (3)-enoyl) botrylactone (9.0 mg), 6-hydroxy-7-deoxybotrylactone (
8 mg
), as well as, cinbotolides B (2.0 mg) and C (
10.1 mg
) (
Moraga et al., 2016
), and the metabolites botcinin H (
21
) (5.0 mg), botcinin I (
